	<item>
		<title>By: Kevin Werbach</title>
		<link>http://werblog.com/2005/07/ical-alternatives/#comment-45</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Kevin Werbach]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 07 Jul 2005 10:59:41 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://werbach.com/wordpress/?p=1241#comment-45</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Gen, I don&#039;t use Mail.app, so that&#039;s not a problem. But in any event, I rarely use my email program to receive calendar items.  If I do, 90% of them come from someone running Outlook.

I do appreciate your help.  I have various kinds of questions and problems that pop up on an unpredictable basis. I keep hearing about the genius bar, but I assume it&#039;s not essentially Mac consultants who work for free for an indefinite period of time -- if so, no one would buy Applecare.  And I have to assume that a question like &quot;how do I switch away from Apple&#039;s iCal?&quot; isn&#039;t the kind of thing they are there to answer.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Gen, I don&#8217;t use Mail.app, so that&#8217;s not a problem. But in any event, I rarely use my email program to receive calendar items.  If I do, 90% of them come from someone running Outlook.</p>
<p>I do appreciate your help.  I have various kinds of questions and problems that pop up on an unpredictable basis. I keep hearing about the genius bar, but I assume it&#8217;s not essentially Mac consultants who work for free for an indefinite period of time &#8212; if so, no one would buy Applecare.  And I have to assume that a question like &#8220;how do I switch away from Apple&#8217;s iCal?&#8221; isn&#8217;t the kind of thing they are there to answer.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
	</item>
	<item>
		<title>By: Gen</title>
		<link>http://werblog.com/2005/07/ical-alternatives/#comment-44</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Gen]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 07 Jul 2005 01:59:50 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://werbach.com/wordpress/?p=1241#comment-44</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Kevin, if you switch to Entourage, you ought to give up mail.app too.  I.e Mail.app and iCal are a pair.

If you want to visualize an all day item in iCal set it not to &quot;all day&quot; but set it to 9am-5pm or whatever, and you&#039;ll see it there, not just at the top.

We, your readers and fellow Mac users, are happy to help, but you might be better served by setting up a time at your local Mac store Genius Bar and go in with a big list of questions for them to answer- this is what they do for a living.  If you want it, you can sign up for their premium service which gives you priority as well.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Kevin, if you switch to Entourage, you ought to give up mail.app too.  I.e Mail.app and iCal are a pair.</p>
<p>If you want to visualize an all day item in iCal set it not to &#8220;all day&#8221; but set it to 9am-5pm or whatever, and you&#8217;ll see it there, not just at the top.</p>
<p>We, your readers and fellow Mac users, are happy to help, but you might be better served by setting up a time at your local Mac store Genius Bar and go in with a big list of questions for them to answer- this is what they do for a living.  If you want it, you can sign up for their premium service which gives you priority as well.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
	</item>
